Similar and clearly related to 

M. peninsularis


sp. n.

, from which it can be isolated by having the vertex laterally polished (
Fig. 27
) (vs. extensively areolate/foveolate, with some foveolae extending to temple, 
Fig. 81
); interocellar carinae weakly defined, laterally blending with areolation (
Fig. 26
) (vs. uniform and clearly isolated from areolation, 
Fig. 79
); gena (
Fig. 28
) and mesopleuron (
Fig. 33
) weakly or sparsely foveolate (vs. coarsely foveolate, 
Figs 80, 82
); scutellum lateral area polished, with a narrow submarginal channel (
Fig. 31
) (vs. taken by deep, straight crenulation, 
Fig. 83
); fore and mid coxae mostly polished (
Fig. 32
) (vs. densely coarsely foveolate, 
Fig. 84
); and the petiole somewhat long, on Mexican specimens 5.04–6.07 longer than maximum dorsal width (vs. 4.77–5.29). Fore wing vein 1M at point of connexion with vein 1Cu is somewhat arched, generating a blunt angle (vs. straight, producing a sharp angle), and crossvein 1cu­a meets 1Cu weakly but distinctly beyond point of conexion of 1M/1Cu (vs. nearly opposite). However, the stability of the last two features needs confirmation, since few specimens were examined, and venation in stephanids may vary even between right and left wings of the same specimen.

